article.description: Seimone Augustus scored six of her 28 points in overtime to help the Minnesota Lynx beat the Connecticut Sun 77-73 Wednesday night.
article.headline: Lynx hold off Sun in OT for just third win in 21 games
article.linkText: Augustus carries lowly Lynx to OT win over Sun
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The pieces seem to be coming together for the
Minnesota Lynx.

	   Seimone Augustus scored 28 points, and Lindsey Harding made the
go-ahead basket in overtime as the Lynx defeated the Connecticut
Sun 77-73 on Wednesday night.

	   Nicole Ohlde added 18 points and eight rebounds for Minnesota
(2-9), which ended a two-game losing streak and won for just the
third time in 21 games dating to last season.

	   "For the people who come to watch this team on a daily basis,
we're making strides," said first-year Lynx coach Don Zierden,
whose club won before an announced crowd of 9,382.

	   The loss spoiled the homecoming of Sun guard Lindsay Whalen, a
former star at the University of Minnesota. Whalen finished with 10
points, seven rebounds and five assists.

	   "It's cool to see family and friends and everybody," the
Hutchinson native said.

	   Connecticut lost its second straight and dropped to 4-4, but the
Sun are considered among the WNBA's elite teams. Connecticut led
the league with 26-8 records each of the past two years.

	   "Hopefully all of the bad stuff is behind us," Augustus said.

	   The "bad stuff" for the Lynx includes a franchise-worst 0-7
start to this season and a 10-24 mark last year that was the
second-worst in the WNBA.

	   Minnesota, though, has some building blocks to work with,
including shooting guard Augustus, the 2006 WNBA Rookie of the
Year, and point guard Harding, this year's No. 1 overall pick.

	   Harding's layup with 2:06 left in overtime put Minnesota ahead
for good at 73-71.

	   "She came up big," Augustus said of Harding. "Lindsay Whalen
played solid basketball tonight, but I think I have to give the
edge to my Lindsey."

	   Whalen made two free throws with 1:30 remaining to bring the Sun
within 75-73, but Augustus hit two free throws with 18.1 seconds
left.

	   "It's big because we get the confidence," said Lynx forward
Svetlana Abrosimova, one of the few veteran's on the WNBA's
youngest team. "It's going to help us in the long run."

	   Abrosimova's two free throws with 2:16 remaining in the fourth
quarter put Minnesota up 67-65. The Sun's Katie Douglas then made a
driving layup with 14.9 seconds left to tie it at 67.

	   Asjha Jones had 22 points and 10 rebounds to lead the Sun, who
came into the game averaging 81.1 points per game. Minnesota ended
a four-game losing skid to Connecticut.

	   "I think they are a very together team" Zierden, a former
Timberwolves assistant coach, said about the Lynx. "I think it
talks about their intestinal fortitude."
